Hello everyone,
I’m Deepan, and I’d like to describe myself as someone who views the world with clarity—through a black-and-white perspective. While I believe in drawing clear distinctions between right and wrong, I’m also open to reevaluating my views when presented with valid reasoning. Flexibility in thought is something I deeply value.

I tend to maintain a calm demeanor and prefer to quietly support initiatives rather than engage in outward displays of enthusiasm. That said, I strongly believe in listening, understanding different perspectives, thoughtful discussions—even if it means occasionally being perceived as a bit argumentative. I see this as a way to better grasp others’ points of view and address their challenges.

Blog#2 Is Life Black and White?

SO , Is Life black and white?

HEHEHE I wish 

But really , can everything be divided into two categories , right or wrong , good or bad ,

?? (okay , maybe that's just me)

ANYWAYS , can we really sort every person , thought , decision , action , moment into TWO little boxes and call it a day?

So , why to think Black and White?

ITS SIMPLE
ITS NEAT

Its like putting your clothes into two boxes , dirty ones and the clean ones
where No "I just wore this pant for a Half a day " exists.......

Thinking in Black and white saves energy , Mental energy , Emotional energy .
Less Thinking = More chill = (dumb?)
if its
Right = do it?
Wrong = don't do it?

But What about the "I just wore this pant for a Half a day " part??

Now , here comes the annoying , irritating mess....

Where everything is kinda right and kinda wrong.
Where you say "I’m doing this for the right reasons” but humans are biased , who decides that your "reasons" are right and wrong?

Where someone hurts you but also didn’t mean to.
Where you’re not wrong… but not exactly right either.


UGH.

It’s annoying, right? I mean, who decided life should come with moral plot twists and situational plot holes?

Two Sides of the Coin… and Then Like, 57 Edges
(By the way , if u ever flipped a coin in google or with any other ai , it mostly gives heads!! )

Black and white thinking is kinda like that “you’re either with me or against me” mindset. Dramatic. Toxic. Sounds like a reality show.
But what about

The kid who lies to protect their sibling?
The person who steals cuz he is in a desperate need?
The villain in a movie who had a tragic backstory and now you’re like… okay maybe I get them a

?

Life isn’t a coin. It’s more like a 20-sided dice, or a chaotic game of Uno where someone keeps adding reverse cards.

Is Right Always Right?
Let’s say stealing is wrong.
Cool??Agreed??

Now 
Imagine someone stealing food because their family is starving.
Still wrong?
Maybe.
Still

wrong?
Maybe not.

There’s this thing called
—and it LOVES messing things up for me.
Wait So What to do with all this Confusion?

. I was hoping you’d have the answer. if u does (email me : deepanramaraju123@gmail.com) 

Okay, imagine this: life is one giant math function.
Yeah, I know. Ew. Math. But stay with me.

Each decision? A function.
Each situation? A parameter.
The output? “Right” or “Wrong” (or sometimes just

Then yeah, everyone’s running their own messed-up emotional Python code in real-time.

And here’s the kicker: you don’t
this function once and live happily ever after.

You’re tweaking it constantly.

Every person you meet, every mistake you make, every convo that starts with “no offense but…”—they all tweak the function a little.
LIKE
Hmm okay maybe yelling at people isn’t always wrong if they’re chewing with their mouth open.
Maybe lying is bad unless it’s about pretending to like someone’s cooking.
Maybe I misjudged that guy from the first week of college and he’s not actually a menace to society.

. Function updated.
Like a moral software patch.
Now you’re running version 9.4.2 of
“How I Decide Stuff: With Less Bias"

Every person you meet is like a new test case.
Every dumb thing you do is a bug report.

So maybe it’s not about solving whether u r right or wrong once and for all.
Maybe it’s just about rewriting your internal code until it throws
